                    <abstract type="content" lang="eng">It is a common concern that pricing pressure by powerful buyers discourages suppliers&apos; R&amp;D investments. Employing a simple monopsonist - competitive upstream industry - framework, this paper qualifies this view in two respects. First, the monopsonist has an incentive to subsidize upstream R&amp;D which yields more upstream R&amp;D and higher profits in both industries than the monopsonist&apos;s commitment to higher prices. Secondly, in the presence of intra-industry R&amp;D spillovers between upstream firms, the monopsonist has an even stronger incentive to finance upstream R&amp;D. If the monopsonist finances more than fifty percent of suppliers R&amp;D efforts, R&amp;D investments in upstream industry will be higher than in the case of buyer competition. 

JEL Classification : O31, O32, L13, L20 

